{"kind":"article","identifier":{"url":"doc:\/\/SwiftCrossUI\/documentation\/SwiftCrossUI\/DefaultBackend","interfaceLanguage":"swift"},"abstract":[{"text":"An adaptive backend which uses different backends under the hood depending on the target operating system.","type":"text"}],"schemaVersion":{"major":0,"patch":0,"minor":3},"seeAlsoSections":[{"identifiers":["doc:\/\/SwiftCrossUI\/documentation\/SwiftCrossUI\/AppKitBackend","doc:\/\/SwiftCrossUI\/documentation\/SwiftCrossUI\/UIKitBackend","doc:\/\/SwiftCrossUI\/documentation\/SwiftCrossUI\/WinUIBackend","doc:\/\/SwiftCrossUI\/documentation\/SwiftCrossUI\/GtkBackend","doc:\/\/SwiftCrossUI\/documentation\/SwiftCrossUI\/Gtk3Backend"],"generated":true}],"primaryContentSections":[{"content":[{"level":2,"text":"Overview","type":"heading","anchor":"Overview"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"The beauty of SwiftCrossUI is that you can write your app once and have it look native everywhere. For this reason I recommend using DefaultBackend unless you’ve got particular constraints. It uses ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftCrossUI\/documentation\/SwiftCrossUI\/AppKitBackend"},{"text":" on macOS, ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftCrossUI\/documentation\/SwiftCrossUI\/WinUIBackend"},{"text":" on Window, ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftCrossUI\/documentation\/SwiftCrossUI\/GtkBackend"},{"text":" on Linux, and on ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftCrossUI\/documentation\/SwiftCrossUI\/UIKitBackend"},{"text":" on iOS\/tvOS.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"If you’re using DefaultBackend, you can override the underlying backend during compilation by setting the ","type":"text"},{"code":"SCUI_DEFAULT_BACKEND","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" environment variable to the name of the desired backend. This is useful when